vectorData.altText: 13. Which intercostal nerves contribute to the innervation of the abdominal wall?

The thickness of the abdominal wall is innervated by branches of the T7 - T12, and L1 spinal nerves. The ventral rami of the thoracic spinal nerves form the T7 - T11 intercostal nerves, which emerge from the costal margin to enter the abdominal wall, and the subcostal nerves.

In the case of the L1 spinal nerves, the ventral rami form the iliohypogastric and ilioinguinal nerves. 
These nerves provide:

somatic motor fibres to the skeletal muscle of the abdominal wall
sensory fibres to the thickness of the abdominal wall, from the skin to the parietal peritoneum, and 
sympathetic postganglionic fibres to vascular smooth muscle, and to both arrector pili muscle and glands of the skin.
That's right!  Ventral rami of thoracic spinal nerves form T7-T11 intercostal nerves which contribute to innervation of the abdominal wall.
